  "prompt": "How many ways can a 4-digit number be formed using the digits 3, 4, 4, 4, 5, 6, 6 and 7?",
  "response": "To determine the number of ways a 4-digit number can be formed using the digits 3, 4, 4, 4, 5, 6, 6, and 7, we will consider the different combinations of these digits and take into account any repetitions.\n\nFirst, we will partition the digits into groups based on how many times each digit appears:\n- 3 (appears 1 time)\n- 4 (appears 3 times)\n- 5 (appears 1 time)\n- 6 (appears 2 times)\n- 7 (appears 1 time)\n\nWe need to pick 4 digits from these available ones and permutations will depend on how many digits are repeated.\n\n### Case Analysis Based on Digit Choice\n\n**Case 1: No repeated digits**\n- Choose any four from 3, 4, 5, 6, 7.\n  - The choices are: 3, 4, 5, 6; 3, 4, 5, 7; 3, 4, 6, 7; 3, 5, 6, 7; 4, 5, 6, 7.\n  - So, total choices = 5.\n  - Each choice of four digits can be arranged in \\(4!\\) ways.\n  - Total arrangements for this case = \\(5 \\times 24 = 120\\).\n\n**Case 2: One digit repeated twice**\n- For instance, digit 4 or 6 appearing twice among the chosen digits.\n- We can have two configurations: choosing digits where either 4 or 6 is repeated along with two other distinct digits:\n  - 4 appears twice: {4, 4, x, y} where x, y are chosen from 3, 5, 6, 7 (4)\n  - 6 appears twice: {6, 6, x, y} where x, y are chosen from 3, 4, 5, 7 (4)\n  - Number of ways to choose x, y for each configuration = \\( \\binom{4}{2}\\).\n  - Total configurations = \\(4 \\times (3, 5, 6, 7)\\times 12, 120\\).\n\n  - {4, 4, 3, 5}, {4, 4, 3, 6}, {4, 4, 3, 7}, {4, 4, 5, 6}, {4, 4, 5, 7}, {4, 4, 6, 7}.\n  - {6, 6, movement 4}, {6, 6, 7}, {6, 6, 3}, {4, 5, 7}.\n\nWhen repeated same digit twice 4 repeated (two).\n7 total repeated reconfigurations the digits can arranged 24 ways = 24\u00d76 = 144.\n\n### Total ways arrangements:\nNow adding configurations:\n120+144 = 264\n```\n\nNote:\nCases assuming repeated combinations accordingly remaining the multiple permutations repeated particulatively consider setups deletions).\nMacros reflect:\nCase 1=120.\nCase 2, combination repeated assumptions multiply (proper detailed case):\n\nGiven noted results configurations checking combination assumptions reflecting multiple arrangements confirming:\n```",
